      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "89cc54084e51b217",
      "text": "\"Definable is only that which has no history\", one reads in [[Friedrich Nietzsche]]'s On the Genealogy of Morals, and this means, conversely, that that which has a history is not definable and thus does not fit into the theoretical grasp.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4c2be3ec1a8c28f2",
      "text": "Michel Foucault has broken down this division of labor between historical and theoretical knowledge. Referring to Nietzsche, he is concerned with explaining singularities from a multiplicity of interactions and strategies even if this multiplicity is only historical and thus always only given with surpluses. The figure of thought that makes it possible not only to narrate but also to explain is the figure of the process. The genealogy of a singularity, according to Foucault, results from the entanglement of process maintenance and process transformation. Compared to the singularity, the process is that general to which a theoretical knowledge can refer, whose question then is: \"How can the insolubility of knowledge and power in the play of multiple interactions and strategies lead to singularities that fix themselves by virtue of their conditions of acceptability, and at the same time to a field of possible openings and indecisions, of possible reversals and shifts that make them fragile and impermanent, which turn those effects into events, no more and no less than events?\"\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5163e1898115b46b",
      "text": "However, this question cannot be answered with the help of the concept of [[Process]], as it should turn out. In chemistry, processes refer too much to results that owe themselves to unclear preconditions, and in jurisprudence, too much to precise preconditions (e.g., the participation of experts) that make it impossible to predict the outcome. The process term is replaced by the [[Network]] term with precisely the implication that Foucault had in mind, namely to be able to reconstruct singularities genealogically. Networks are coherently heterogeneous, consistently fluid, and fuzzy in their boundaries. >> process network"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0e19b6ab49810627",
      "text": "They tend to assemble singular elements into principally singular contexts, into \"plateaus\" or \"systems\" like those of which [[Gilles Deleuze]] spoke: \"In fact, systems have lost absolutely nothing of their living power. Today, in science, in logic, there are first steps towards a theory of so-called open systems based on interactions: they merely renounce linear causalities and transform the concept of time. (...) A system is an ensemble of concepts. It is an open system if the concepts are related to circumstances and no longer to beings, essences. But on the one hand, the concepts are not ready, they are not already there before: concepts have to be invented, created, and in this there is just as much creation and invention as in art or science. Creating new concepts that have a necessity, that has always been the task of philosophy. On the other hand, the concepts are not general ideas of the spirit of the time. On the contrary, they are singularities that have an effect on the ordinary streams of thought: One can think very well without concepts, but as soon as there is concept, there is truly philosophy. This has nothing to do with ideology. A concept is full of critical, political power and freedom. Just and only the power of the system can work out what is good and bad in a construction of concepts, new or not, alive or not. Nothing is absolutely good, everything depends on its use and cleverness in the system context.\"\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fa4cd1146dfc9316",
      "text": "The argument of a genealogy that no longer works with figures of origin but with figures of process or network and therefore does not have to assume creation but only coincidences and their seizing (or missing) as opportunities has become the strong argument of a cultural science that seeks its own theoretical justification alongside the natural and social sciences. If the natural sciences rely on repeatable causality and the social sciences on their interest in the social interconnectedness of social phenomena, cultural studies can give a space to singularities that appear and disappear again without having to be spelled back to natural laws or conform to functional expectations of social order. >> cultural science"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8344b636ece3bdbb",
      "text": "With all this, storytelling loses an innocence that it never had in truth. It becomes a [[Narrative]] that [[contains]] a [[Structure]], the [[Pattern]] of a repeatability, whose fascination consists in the fact that it is preserved even in the medium of singularities. And cultural studies becomes the narrative of narratives, the retelling of stories, which are characterized not least by the fact that stories are also told in them. Cultural studies becomes theoretical by asking about the constitutive role of storytelling in the repetition of particular stories. There were times when this was called ideology critique. Today, one experiments with various conceptual deployments, ranging from process to network to system or even \"field**, signaling that one can no longer be so sure of a philosophy of history that could back an ideology critique. >> narrative contains structure"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "91a02b3df9f21e9e",
      "text": "By reconstructing the history and prehistory of the financial crisis of the years 2006ff. as a history of the singularity of modern finance as a whole, [[Joseph Vogl]] makes masterful use of the license of cultural studies to tell stories about stories. And he complements the cultural-scientific view with a literary-scientific view by not only telling the story of finance and its crises, but at the same time providing information about which common narratives about this finance miss its real problem – or is it already the solution to this problem? – miss the point. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a2f8665af2a34a03",
      "text": "Vogl's book Der [[Souveränitätseffekt]] (The [[Sovereignty Effect]]) is the narrative of a network constellation at the center of which a blind spot, a \"zero point\" (Ernesto Laclau), ensures that a practice is administered that cannot justify itself theoretically, but can only be understood as coping with the state of exception. Vogl is interested in \"a political decision-making power that operates apart from popular sovereignties and bypasses democratic procedures. In the course of the last three hundred years, it has taken on the character of a 'fourth power' in which the formation of capital power cannot be separated from the activation of power capitals. The current dominance of the financial regime is thus understood as the latest manifestation of an economization of governance, which manifests itself in aggressive couplings between political structures and private capital, in the efficient linking of market and power. The notorious juxtaposition of economics and politics proves to be a legend of liberalism and is not sufficient to grasp the genesis and shape of modern exercises of power\" (p. 8)."
