        "id": "5163e1898115b46b",
        "text": "However, this question cannot be answered with the help of the concept of process, as it should turn out. In chemistry, processes refer too much to results that owe themselves to unclear preconditions, and in jurisprudence, too much to precise preconditions (e.g., the participation of experts) that make it impossible to predict the outcome. The process term is replaced by the network term with precisely the implication that Foucault had in mind, namely to be able to reconstruct singularities genealogically. Networks are coherently heterogeneous, consistently fluid, and fuzzy in their boundaries. "
