        "id": "fa4cd1146dfc9316",
        "text": "The argument of a genealogy that no longer works with figures of origin but with figures of process or network and therefore does not have to assume creation but only coincidences and their seizing (or missing) as opportunities has become the strong argument of a cultural science that seeks its own theoretical justification alongside the natural and social sciences. If the natural sciences rely on repeatable causality and the social sciences on their interest in the social interconnectedness of social phenomena, cultural studies can give a space to singularities that appear and disappear again without having to be spelled back to natural laws or conform to functional expectations of social order.\n"
